<subSubSection pageId="80" pageNumber="81" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="80.[151,1437,582,1579]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1338,1363]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">Remarks.</emphasis>
This new species differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Evans, 1966" authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1966" box="[660,927,1338,1363]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Anisepyris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="80" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigripes">
<emphasis box="[660,782,1339,1363]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">A. nigripes</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[789,927,1338,1363]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81" refId="ref280374" refString="Evans, H. E. (1966) A revision of the genus Anisepyris Kieffer (Hymenoptera. Bethylidae). Studia Entomologica, 9, 1 - 120." type="journal article">Evans, 1966</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by having the antennal flagellomeres serrate; the pronotal disc with its transverse pronotal carina and posterior pronotal sulcus followed by a series of great foveae; the metapostnotum with the first metapostnotal carina and metapostnotal-propodeal suture convergent; and the mesopleuron with the anterior fovea longer than the posterior, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1966" box="[1090,1221,1447,1470]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Anisepyris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="80" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigripes">
<emphasis box="[1090,1221,1447,1470]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">A. nigripes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the antennal flagellomeres filiform; the pronotal disc with its transverse pronotal carina and posterior pronotal sulcus not followed by foveae; the metapostnotum with the first metapostnotal carina and metapostnotal-propodeal suture fused posteriorly; and the mesopleuron with the anterior fovea as long as the posterior.
</paragraph>
